# Fixture IRI-005: authority-less absolute IRIs (urn:, tag:, data:)
#
# RFC 3986 §3 defines an absolute URI as scheme ":" hier-part [ "?" query ].
# An authority (`//host`) is optional.  The following schemes are absolute
# WITHOUT an authority component: urn:, tag:, isbn:, doi:, data:, etc.
#
# N-Triples (and Turtle) require absolute IRIs in subject, predicate, and
# object position.  The absoluteness test is:  does the IRI have a scheme?
# NOT: does the IRI contain `://`?
#
# Hypothesis: An implementation that tests absoluteness with a regex like
# `^https?://` or a check for the literal substring `://` will reject
# valid `urn:` and `tag:` IRIs as non-absolute, raising a fatal parse
# error on conformant input.
#
# Spec: RFC 3986 §3 (URI syntax components)
#       RFC 2141 (URN syntax)
#       W3C RDF Concepts §3.1 (absolute IRI definition)

# urn: scheme — no authority, opaque path
<urn:example:a-resource> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <urn:example:Class> .

# urn: ISBN
<urn:isbn:0451450523> <http://schema.org/name> "The Name of the Rose" .

# urn: with fragment
<urn:example:foo#bar> <http://example.org/pred/ref> <urn:example:foo> .

# tag: scheme (RFC 4151) — authority-like but not an HTTP authority
<tag:example.org,2024:resource-1> <http://example.org/pred/label> "tagged-resource" .

# data: URI (RFC 2397) — no host
<data:,hello> <http://example.org/pred/content> "inline-data" .
